ass table.</Para></LeadPara></HandL><TailParas fid="td"><Para>While access to streaming services on your room's TV is now as standard as air conditioning, hotels are doubling down to offer the unexpected, too:</Para><Para>For the Music Fans</Para><Para>At the Elizabeth Hotel in Fort Collins, Colo., every room comes equipped with a vintage-style Crosley Keepsake turntable and access to 1,000 groovy LPs by artists from the Lumineers to Billy Idol. Should you tire of spiffing up your air-guitar riffs, the hotel offers a lending library of instruments (provided by the Bohemian Foundation), including an Avian Songbird guitar and a 76-note Yamaha NP-32 keyboard.</Para><Para>For the Film Buffs</Para><Para>The Entertainment Suite at the Landmark Mandarin Oriental, Hong Kong not only tops most any other room for cinematic experiences, it tops itself. Should its 85-inch Bang &amp; Olufsen Avant Series 4K TV and sound system, massive film selection and popcorn dispenser not feel indulgent enough, guests can summon from the ceiling a 5,000 lumen Sony projector and a 13-foot x 11.5-foot screen. Elsewhere, Marriott's Moxy hotels let guests log into Pandora, Netflix and Hulu accounts to continue whatever binge they'd begun back home.</Para><Para>For the Sports Nuts</Para><Para>We've mentioned the risks of practicing your golf swing by the ice bucket. But what about in-room cycling? On request, select Westin hotels will outfit rooms with exercise equipment, including Peloton bikes that let you participate in live-streamed spin classes. For more passive enjoyment, Sheraton hotels offer baseball fans access to MLB.TV. Beyond viewing all 2,430 regular season matchups in stunning 60 FPS quality, guests can use the DVR controls to pause the action when room service arrives.</Para><Para>For the Gamers</Para><Para>The Graduate Hotel chain, which focuses on college towns, is attuned to geek needs. Stay in the Family Suite at the Lincoln, Neb. location, and you can school the kids in Space Invaders or Frogger on vintage Atari 2600s. In the nostalgia-inducing Game Suites, play Donkey Kong Jr. or Ms. Pac-Man on full-size arcade cabinets. In the Camp Wandawega suite at the Madison, Wis., location, guests can choose from the 21 games preinstalled on the in-room Super NES Classic Edition consoles.</Para></TailParas><Byline fid="by" index="field">By Matthew Kronsberg </Byline><Credit fid="cr" index="field"></Credit><Contact fid="ct" index="field"></Contact><Notes fid="rf" index="field"></Notes><Art fid="art" index="field"></Art><Copyright fid="cy" index="field">Copyright 2018 Dow Jones &amp; Company, Inc. All Rights Reserved. </Copyright></Article></ArchiveDoc><AdocTOC adoctype="article"><Item size="0" ref="distdoc:archive/ArchiveDoc::Article" type="arttext"></Item><Item size="0" ref="distdoc:archive/InvertText" type="invtext"></Item><Item subtype="primary" size="0" ref="https://www.wsj.com/articles/how-hotels-are-upping-the-ante-on-in-room-entertainment-1521737113" type="webpage"></Item></AdocTOC></DistDoc>

